<div id="review_758793885" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/758793885" />
    <a title="Lisajean" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22100142-lisajean"><img alt="Lisajean" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1599969279p2/22100142.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/758793885?book_show_action=true">Nov 06, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lisajean" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lisajean" href="/user/show/22100142-lisajean">Lisajean</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22100142-lisajean?shelf=italy">italy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22100142-lisajean?shelf=nobel">nobel</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22100142-lisajean?shelf=ward-500">ward-500</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22100142-lisajean?shelf=plays">plays</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22100142-lisajean?shelf=bloom-western-canon">bloom-western-canon</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer758793885" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8700269359674660851">This is one of my all-time favorite plays. I like Pirandello because his works wrestle with the same questions in different ways and <i>Six Characters in Search of an Author</i> is probably the best exploration of the questions that he&apos;s most concerned with. It makes the audience question the nature of theatre and their place as people getting enjoyment from the suffering of others, even if those others are imaginary characters. On a larger level, it asks how the act of observation changes reality and </span>
  <span id="freeText8700269359674660851" style="display:none">This is one of my all-time favorite plays. I like Pirandello because his works wrestle with the same questions in different ways and <i>Six Characters in Search of an Author</i> is probably the best exploration of the questions that he's most concerned with. It makes the audience question the nature of theatre and their place as people getting enjoyment from the suffering of others, even if those others are imaginary characters. On a larger level, it asks how the act of observation changes reality and shows how subjective people's conception of truth can be. I've read a number of Pirandello's other plays and, although they don't have the metatheatrical aspect that his masterpiece does, they're just as concerned with subjectivity and truth. He won the Nobel Prize in 1934 for "his almost magical power to turn psychological analysis into good theatre," but I think that Pirandello goes beyond the merely psychological to delve into philosophical and metaphysical questions. He's a pleasure to read. </span>
  <a data-text-id="8700269359674660851" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


