        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1525433298" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11638385561513657875">A while back, when I made an attempt at creative writing, all the characters in my story seemed to be full of possibilities at first, and then became more and more willful and awry as the story progressed. I blamed this on my lack of foreplanning and writing experience, and usually just abandoned my creations that turned out like the unanticipated Frankenstein. <br/><br/>I got a similar feeling when I was acting or directing in our college drama club. At first reading, I&apos;m clueless to what&apos;s facing me but</span>
  <span id="freeText11638385561513657875" style="display:none">A while back, when I made an attempt at creative writing, all the characters in my story seemed to be full of possibilities at first, and then became more and more willful and awry as the story progressed. I blamed this on my lack of foreplanning and writing experience, and usually just abandoned my creations that turned out like the unanticipated Frankenstein. <br /><br />I got a similar feeling when I was acting or directing in our college drama club. At first reading, I'm clueless to what's facing me but when I (or the actors that I'm directing) put our voice and gestures into those blank words, the characters all turn out to be something quite unexpected with a life of its own. This was aggravated by the fact that the characters were interpreted in different angles by each of the actors, the director, and the prop team (and possibly by the author if the author could have been present in our amateur drama club). Had it not been a collective effort, I would have gladly given up on the project (good riddance to you all!) and resorted to a solitary internal reenactment of my own version of the play. Alas, the show must go on, and I was forced to be molded into someone else's idea of the drama.<br /><br />I was also unsettled by my first performing experience, or rather the end of my first performance. After about an hour of being an avatar of someone else's figment of imagination, the curtain closed down on us with the lights slowly fading away. As I stepped up to bow to the audience, I had the strangest sensation of being deserted by the character that remained and lived on in the play while I became the empty shell, or a dream or a ghost of the character instead of the other way around. <br /><br />As I read and then watched the play of Pirandello, I was reminded of the aforementioned personal impressions of drama (and I was just an amateur with not even a hint of method acting in me!) and I couldn't help sympathizing with both the characters and the director (manager). This meta-drama delves through the metaphysical elements of theatre and fantasy by reversing the roles of both the creatr and created, the actors and the characters, and finds the common ground between our fantasy and reality, as stated in the play: "nature uses the instrument of human fantasy in order to pursue her high creative purpose." <br /><br />This common ground, which is called 'absurdity' is made explicit many times in the play by the characters' argument in that the actors are no more real than the characters themselves and that reality is no less absurd or plausible than what is on stage: "... you know well that life is full of infinite absudities, which strangely enough, do not even need to appear plausible, since they are true."<br /><br />The multifaceted existence of the characters also points out the clashes between different interpretations and between people in reality. It also reminded me of my past frictions in the drama club and in my real life as well: <br /><br />"how can we ever come to an understanding if I put in the words I utter the sense and value of things as I see them; while you who listen to me must inevitably translate them according to the conception of things each one of you has within himself"<br /><br />"We believe this conscience to be a single thing, but it is many-sided. There is one for this person, and another for that."<br /><br />"It is merely to show you that one is born to life in many forms, in many shapes, as tree, or as stone, as water, as butterfly, or as woman. So one may also born a character in a play."<br /><br />Thus the characters reveal both our limitations in communication and Pirandello sometimes use this misunderstanding as comic relief: "Is it my fault if France won't send us any more good comedies, and we are reduced to putting on Pirandello's works, where nobody understands anything, and where the author plays the fool with us all?"<br /><br />However, even after the release of self-derisive wit, the audience is reminded again by the characters of the cruelty of this 'game of art' which is for them their 'sole reality'. Susan Sontag's 'Regarding the Pain of Others' was a jab at the secondary violence of the representation of violence. Is Pirandello warning against the inured and desensitized audience to the painful reality behind the seeming illusion of drama, and beseeching for their awareness of the 'real' suffering and tragedy beneath the facade of comedy?<br /><br />"I feel what I think; and I seem to be philosophizing only for those who do not think what they feel"<br /><br />"For man never reasons so much and becomes so introspective as when he suffers."<br /><br />However the interpretation or reenactment of the characters end up, the characters seem to have an endless fate (or will) that is independent of the author, the actor or the director and live on after the lights are dimmed and the curtains drop. This feeling haunted me long after I stopped acting and I got caught up in these two lines where the characters at first asked the manager to live only for a moment in the actors, but then eventually turns the table around to reveal the ephemeral and fragile existence of our own 'reality'.<br /><br />The Father: We want to live.<br />The Manager (ironically): For Eternity?<br />The Father: No, sir, only for a moment.... in you.<br /><br />The Father: Ours is an immutable reality which should make you shudder when you approach us if you are really conscious of the fact that your reality is a mere transitory and fleeting illusion, taking this form today and that tomorrow.<br /><br />Another line put me on a guilt trip as I remembered all those stories and characters I rejected in the end. If we, too, are a creation of God, are we also as willful and yet helpless to change our own fate?<br /><br />"When a character is born, he acquires at once such an independence, even of his own author, that he can be imagined by everybody even in many other situations where the author never dreamed of placing him; and so he acquires for himself a meaning which the author never thought of giving him.<br /><br />.... Imagine such a misfortune for characters as I have described to you: to be born of an author's fantasy, and be denied life by him; and then answer me if these characters left alive, and yet without life, weren't right in doing what they did do and are doing now, after they have attempted everything in their power to persuade him to give them their stage life."<br /><br />Although I liked existentialist novels by Camus and Sartre, I never really enjoyed Beckett's absurdist play 'Waiting for Godot'. Maybe it was because I haven't had enough of both the stage of life and theatre (I was in highschool). I certainly appreciated Pirandello's play both in book and on screen. Some charitable soul uploaded this BBC production on youtube, and the performances are marvelous.<br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/WvWCfIYPZK0?list=PLPxTfzeDGPUu-3GE0VD7Hqx8KwItGyu1W">https://youtu.be/WvWCfIYPZK0?list=PLP...</a><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/I_FV4-BM9IA?list=PLPxTfzeDGPUu-3GE0VD7Hqx8KwItGyu1W">https://youtu.be/I_FV4-BM9IA?list=PLP...</a><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/1gwDorSE8pg?list=PLPxTfzeDGPUu-3GE0VD7Hqx8KwItGyu1W">https://youtu.be/1gwDorSE8pg?list=PLP...</a><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/R_ygc3UGo6g?list=PLPxTfzeDGPUu-3GE0VD7Hqx8KwItGyu1W">https://youtu.be/R_ygc3UGo6g?list=PLP...</a><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/nfUuTZjG3kI?list=PLPxTfzeDGPUu-3GE0VD7Hqx8KwItGyu1W">https://youtu.be/nfUuTZjG3kI?list=PLP...</a><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/0lr8Mjx1IAE?list=PLPxTfzeDGPUu-3GE0VD7Hqx8KwItGyu1W">https://youtu.be/0lr8Mjx1IAE?list=PLP...</a><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/CjZfQk047oI?list=PLPxTfzeDGPUu-3GE0VD7Hqx8KwItGyu1W">https://youtu.be/CjZfQk047oI?list=PLP...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="11638385561513657875" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


