  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2928952738" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2928952738" />
    <a title="Ananya M" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9613048-ananya-m"><img alt="Ananya M" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1642570059p2/9613048.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2928952738?book_show_action=true">Feb 09, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ananya M" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ananya M" href="/user/show/9613048-ananya-m">Ananya M</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2928952738" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17763001844275827287">I have never read a play this unique, I am in awe. It follows a theatre group about to begin their rehearsal for a Pirandello play, the manager is going about telling them what to do, and how much he hates Pirandello’s plays. There is no real set, just the stage; no scenes, just a mix of confusion and madness. <br/>Six people enter the scene saying that they were characters looking for an author. The manager tries to kick them out of the theatre, calling out their outlandish ideas, but the characters</span>
  <span id="freeText17763001844275827287" style="display:none">I have never read a play this unique, I am in awe. It follows a theatre group about to begin their rehearsal for a Pirandello play, the manager is going about telling them what to do, and how much he hates Pirandello’s plays. There is no real set, just the stage; no scenes, just a mix of confusion and madness. <br />Six people enter the scene saying that they were characters looking for an author. The manager tries to kick them out of the theatre, calling out their outlandish ideas, but the characters promise him a great drama, so he listens. The actors are outraged by this, wondering why they’re still here and why their rehearsals aren’t going on. These characters, simply called the father, the mother, the step daughter, the son, the child and the boy, begin their drama. They act out their story and the manager decides to take it upon himself to make a real play out of it and gets someone to write down what they’re saying. <br />As the characters go about with their dialogues, the manager starts to change things according to his convenience, the actors, and the props that they have. The father pleads with him to not replace them with the actors. The manager is shocked at the suggestion that they would act it out themselves, in public and the father tells him that this is their only reality. They have no other story, no other option because the author has only written so much for them, which is why they’re looking for another author to give them something more. <br />The lines in this play were so unique and really showed the reality of how the author has no power over the characters once they’re created and he has to follow what the characters are doing. Once the author creates a character there is no going back. The characters here think that the author abandoned them out of disgust for the story that he wrote himself. The play ends with the manager saying he wasted an entire day on them and this is something he has never seen before in his life. </span>
  <a data-text-id="17763001844275827287" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


